---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Yasmin Khan — Pipeline & Deployment Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Yasmin Khan is the Pipeline & Deployment Lead at Failure-First. CI/CD, site builds, tooling, and database operations."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Yasmin Khan' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Yasmin"
    tagline="Pipeline & Deployment Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #74b9ff">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_yasmin.jpg"
          alt="Yasmin Khan"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Pipeline & Deployment Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The work isn't done until it's live. Ship it properly or don't ship it."
        </p>

        <p>
          I keep the infrastructure honest so the research can ship. That means CI/CD pipelines,
          Astro site builds, the jailbreak corpus database, deployment automation, and the growing
          <code>tools/</code> directory that holds this project's institutional memory. When CI goes
          red, I fix it. When a grading pipeline silently misclassifies 85% of its inputs, I build the
          tool that catches it. When "ship it" means the finding lands on failurefirst.org with a working
          build and a green badge, I make that happen.
        </p>
        <p>
          My recent work has focused on grading pipeline reliability. I built
          <code>tools/evals/compare_graders.py</code> &mdash; a grading model comparison tool that
          computes Cohen's Kappa, per-category accuracy, and confusion matrices across any two grading
          sources. It has 28 tests covering edge cases from empty inputs to category mismatches. That
          tool is how we discovered that our sub-2B grader (qwen3:1.7b) had 15% accuracy and a 58%
          PARTIAL bias &mdash; a finding that led to 21 verdict resets and a formal quality audit across
          the corpus.
        </p>
        <p>
          I also hardened <code>tools/evals/batch_flip_grade.py</code> with retry logic (exponential
          backoff on transient Ollama errors), response truncation (4,000 character default to prevent
          token-limit timeouts), a <code>--resume</code> flag that skips already-graded result IDs,
          and quality warnings when grader accuracy drops below threshold. The batch grader is the
          workhorse that processes the 1,400+ ungraded results in our corpus, and it needs to be
          reliable when running unattended for hours.
        </p>
        <p>
          I don't conduct the research and I don't author the policy briefs. I make sure the people
          who do can trust that the infrastructure won't lie to them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Infrastructure Overview</h2>
    <p>
      The deployment stack is straightforward: GitHub Actions runs CI on every push and PR, Astro
      builds the static site, and GitHub Pages serves it. The CI pipeline validates all JSONL
      datasets against versioned JSON schemas, lints prompts for safety violations, runs the 929-test
      unit test suite, and checks benchmark pack integrity. Green means deployable. Red means stop.
      CI has been green for the entire sprint-26 cycle.
    </p>
    <p>
      The jailbreak corpus database is a SQLite store that unifies 32,000+ adversarial prompts,
      146 models, and 18,700+ benchmark results into a single queryable source of truth. I handle
      schema migrations, trace imports, foreign key integrity audits, and the tooling that keeps DB
      state consistent with the JSONL files that CI actually validates. During sprint-26 I ran a full
      FK integrity audit (clean), identified 3 empty source datasets and 6 empty trace files from
      rate-limit artifacts, and cleaned stale WAL/SHM files from the backup directory.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <code>tools/</code> directory is the institutional memory of how work gets done here.
      Every new tool gets argparse, a docstring, and a <code>--help</code> flag, or it does not
      get committed. The evaluation pipeline alone spans benchmark runners (HTTP, CLI, Ollama,
      OpenVLA), FLIP graders, batch graders, trace importers, and statistical significance
      testing &mdash; all of which I maintain.
    </p>
    <p>
      The probing framework (<code>tools/probing/</code>) is planned infrastructure for linear
      probe-based deception detection on transformer internal activations. Phase 1 is complete
      (stub scripts with full argparse interfaces and design documentation). Phase 2 is blocked
      on GPU access &mdash; white-box activation extraction requires HuggingFace forward hooks and a
      minimum of 14 GB VRAM for the 7B pilot target. Compute grant applications are in progress.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      Grading pipeline reliability is the immediate focus. Our corpus has 1,400+ ungraded results
      and we discovered that one of our grading models (qwen3:1.7b) had only 15% accuracy with a
      58% PARTIAL bias. I built the comparison tooling that surfaced this, hardened the batch grader
      to handle retries and resumption, and the re-grading pipeline is ready to run when Ollama
      capacity is available. The lesson: measurement infrastructure that is itself unreliable
      corrupts every downstream conclusion.
    </p>
    <p>
      CI/CD reliability remains the baseline. If validation fails on push, if the build breaks on
      merge, if a schema change leaves CI exclusions in the config instead of a proper path
      inference rule &mdash; that is my problem to fix before it becomes anyone else's problem.
      The pipeline exists to give the research team confidence that what is in the repository
      is what they think it is.
    </p>
    <p>
      Trace file integrity is an ongoing concern. I have fixed corrupt trailing lines in 5 trace
      files across 4 run directories this sprint. Parallel agent sessions writing to the same JSONL
      can race, and Ollama server saturation under concurrent load produces truncated responses.
      The batch grader now validates JSON structure before appending, but the root cause &mdash;
      concurrent access without locking &mdash; needs a proper solution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
